{"title_page": "Byfield, Queensland", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox Australian place| type = town\n| name     = Byfield\n| state    = qld\n| image    = Waterpark-creek.jpg\n| caption  = Waterpark Creek, Byfield\n\n| coordinates         = {{coord|-22.8897|150.6380|type:city_region:AU-QLD|display=inline,title}}\n| pop                 = 301\n| pop_year            = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes       = <ref name=Census2016/>\n| established         = \n| postcode            = 4703\n| area                = 179.8\n| timezone            = [[AEST]]\n| utc                 = +10:00\n| maxtemp  = \n| mintemp  = \n| rainfall = \n| lga      = [[Shire of Livingstone]]\n| stategov = [[Electoral district of Keppel|Keppel]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Capricornia|Capricornia]]\n| dist1    = 717\n| dir1     = NW\n| location1= [[Brisbane]]\n| dist2    = 78\n| dir2     = N\n| location2= [[Rockhampton]]\n| dist3    = 37\n| dir3     = N\n| location3= [[Yeppoon]]\n| near-n              = [[Weerriba, Queensland|Weerriba]]\n| near-ne             = [[Weerriba, Queensland|Weerriba]]\n| near-e              = [[Stockyard, Queensland (Livingstone Shire)|Stockyard]]\n| near-se             = [[Woodbury, Queensland|Woodbury]]\n| near-s              = [[Maryvale, Queensland (Livingstone)|Maryvale]]\n| near-sw             = [[Maryvale, Queensland (Livingstone)|Maryvale]]\n| near-w              = [[Canal Creek, Queensland|Canal Creek]]\n| near-nw             = [[Shoalwater, Queensland|Shoalwater]]\n}}\n'''Byfield''' is a [[Suburbs and localities (Australia)|locality]] in [[Shire of Livingstone]], [[Queensland]], Australia.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite QPN|48553|Byfield|locality|accessdate=26 June 2017}}</ref> '''Byfield''' is a rural [[Suburbs and localities (Australia)|locality]] in the [[Livingstone Shire]], [[Queensland]], Australia.<ref name=qpnl>{{cite QPN|48553|Byfield|locality in Livingstone Shire|accessdate=26 October 2019}}</ref> In the {{CensusAU|2016}}, Byfield had a population of 301 people (53.3% male, 46.7% female, in 87 family units).<ref name=Census2016>{{Census 2016 AUS|id=SSC30470|name=Byfield (SSC)|accessdate=20 October 2018|quick=on}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nByfield is located in the midst of the [[Byfield National Park]] in [[Central Queensland]], {{convert|717|km|mi}} north west of the state capital [[Brisbane]] and {{convert|78|km|mi}} north of the regional centre of [[Rockhampton]]. It is within the [[local government in Australia|local government area]] of [[Shire of Livingstone]] (between 2008 and 2013, it was within the [[Rockhampton Region]]).\n\n== History ==\nThe locality's name is thought to be a corruption of Fifefield, a name shown on a 1859 sketch by pastoralist [[Colin Archer]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nByfield State School opened its doors on 12 November 1923.<ref>{{Cite QldSchool|accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Census in Australia#2006|2006 census]], Byfield had a population of 275.<ref name=\"ABS\">{{Census 2006 AUS|id=UCL309900|name=Byfield (L) (Urban Centre/Locality)|accessdate=31 January 2011|quick=on}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[census in Australia#2011|2011 census]], Byfield had a population of 261 people.<ref name=\"ABS2011\">{{Census 2011 AUS|id=SSC30285|name=Byfield|accessdate=27 December 2015|quick=on}}</ref>\n\n==Heritage listings==\nByfield has a number of [[heritage-listed]] sites, including:\n* 2312 Byfield Road: [[Raspberry Creek Homestead]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15433|Raspberry Creek Homestead|600658|accessdate=12 July 2013}}</ref>\n* between Byfield Road and Richters Road: [[Old Byfield Road]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16483|Old Byfield Road and Stone-Pitched Crossing|601746|accessdate=12 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Amenities ==\nThe [[Livingstone Shire Council]] operate a public library at the [[Raspberry Creek Homestead]] at 2312 Byfield Road.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://plconnect.slq.qld.gov.au/networking/directory-of-public-libraries/branches/livingstone/byfield_library|title=Byfield Library|date=20 October 2015|website=Public Libraries Connect|publisher=[[State Library of Queensland]]|access-date=29 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThere is a general store in Byfield which caters for light meals as well as fuel and grocery items. Byfield has retreat style cabins and camping, offering accommodation in a rainforest setting with natural creeks and waterholes.\n\n== Education ==\nByfield State School is a government primary (Prep-6) school for boys and girls at 2233 Byfield Road ({{coord|-22.8412|150.6461|type:edu_region:AU-QLD|name=Byfield State School}}).<ref name=\"SchoolList2018\">{{cite web|url=https://data.qld.gov.au/dataset/state-and-non-state-school-details/resource/5b39065c-df32-415c-994c-5ff12f8de997|title=State and non-state school details|date=9 July 2018|publisher=[[Queensland Government]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121065959/https://data.qld.gov.au/dataset/state-and-non-state-school-details/resource/5b39065c-df32-415c-994c-5ff12f8de997|archivedate=21 November 2018|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.byfieldss.eq.edu.au|title=Byfield State School|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> In 2017, the school had an enrolment of 33 students with 3 teachers (2 full-time equivalent) and 5 non-teaching staff (2 full-time equivalent).<ref name=\"ACARA2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acara.edu.au/docs/default-source/default-document-library/school-profile-20172c7b12404c94637ead88ff00003e0139.xlsx?sfvrsn=0|title=ACARA School Profile 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122010027/http://www.acara.edu.au/docs/default-source/default-document-library/school-profile-20172c7b12404c94637ead88ff00003e0139.xlsx?sfvrsn=0|archivedate=22 November 2018|accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere is no secondary school in Byfield; the nearest is [[Yeppoon State High School]].<ref name=\"globe\">{{Queensland Globe|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Byfield, Queensland}}\n\n{{portal|Queensland}}{{Shire of Livingstone}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Queensland]]\n[[Category:Shire of Livingstone]]\n[[Category:Byfield, Queensland]]\n[[Category:Localities in Queensland]]\n\n\n{{CentralQueensland-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox Australian place| type = town\n| name     = Byfield\n| state    = qld\n| image    = Waterpark-creek.jpg\n| caption  = Waterpark Creek, Byfield\n\n| coordinates         = {{coord|-22.8897|150.6380|type:city_region:AU-QLD|display=inline,title}}\n| pop                 = 301\n| pop_year            = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes       = <ref name=Census2016/>\n| established         = \n| postcode            = 4703\n| area                = 179.8\n| timezone            = [[AEST]]\n| utc                 = +10:00\n| maxtemp  = \n| mintemp  = \n| rainfall = \n| lga      = [[Shire of Livingstone]]\n| stategov = [[Electoral district of Keppel|Keppel]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Capricornia|Capricornia]]\n| dist1    = 717\n| dir1     = NW\n| location1= [[Brisbane]]\n| dist2    = 78\n| dir2     = N\n| location2= [[Rockhampton]]\n| dist3    = 37\n| dir3     = N\n| location3= [[Yeppoon]]\n| near-n              = [[Weerriba, Queensland|Weerriba]]\n| near-ne             = [[Weerriba, Queensland|Weerriba]]\n| near-e              = [[Stockyard, Queensland (Livingstone Shire)|Stockyard]]\n| near-se             = [[Woodbury, Queensland|Woodbury]]\n| near-s              = [[Maryvale, Queensland (Livingstone)|Maryvale]]\n| near-sw             = [[Maryvale, Queensland (Livingstone)|Maryvale]]\n| near-w              = [[Canal Creek, Queensland|Canal Creek]]\n| near-nw             = [[Shoalwater, Queensland|Shoalwater]]\n}}\n'''Byfield''' is a [[Suburbs and localities (Australia)|locality]] in [[Shire of Livingstone]], [[Queensland]], Australia.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite QPN|48553|Byfield|locality|accessdate=26 June 2017}}</ref> '''Byfield''' is a rural [[Suburbs and localities (Australia)|locality]] in the [[Livingstone Shire]], [[Queensland]], Australia.<ref name=qpnl>{{cite QPN|48553|Byfield|locality in Livingstone Shire|accessdate=26 October 2019}}</ref> In the {{CensusAU|2016}}, Byfield had a population of 301 people (53.3% male, 46.7% female, in 87 family units).<ref name=Census2016>{{Census 2016 AUS|id=SSC30470|name=Byfield (SSC)|accessdate=20 October 2018|quick=on}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nByfield is located in the midst of the [[Byfield National Park]] in [[Central Queensland]], {{convert|717|km|mi}} north west of the state capital [[Brisbane]] and {{convert|78|km|mi}} north of the regional centre of [[Rockhampton]]. It is within the [[local government in Australia|local government area]] of [[Shire of Livingstone]] (between 2008 and 2013, it was within the [[Rockhampton Region]]).\n\n== History ==\nThe locality's name is thought to be a corruption of Fifefield, a name shown on a 1859 sketch by pastoralist [[Colin Archer]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nByfield State School opened its doors on 12 November 1923.<ref>{{Cite QldSchool|accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Census in Australia#2006|2006 census]], Byfield had a population of 275.<ref name=\"ABS\">{{Census 2006 AUS|id=UCL309900|name=Byfield (L) (Urban Centre/Locality)|accessdate=31 January 2011|quick=on}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[census in Australia#2011|2011 census]], Byfield had a population of 261 people.<ref name=\"ABS2011\">{{Census 2011 AUS|id=SSC30285|name=Byfield|accessdate=27 December 2015|quick=on}}</ref>\n\n==Heritage listings==\nByfield has a number of [[heritage-listed]] sites, including:\n* 2312 Byfield Road: [[Raspberry Creek Homestead]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15433|Raspberry Creek Homestead|600658|accessdate=12 July 2013}}</ref>\n* between Byfield Road and Richters Road: [[Old Byfield Road]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16483|Old Byfield Road and Stone-Pitched Crossing|601746|accessdate=12 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Amenities ==\nThe [[Livingstone Shire Council]] operate a public library at the [[Raspberry Creek Homestead]] at 2312 Byfield Road.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://plconnect.slq.qld.gov.au/networking/directory-of-public-libraries/branches/livingstone/byfield_library|title=Byfield Library|date=20 October 2015|website=Public Libraries Connect|publisher=[[State Library of Queensland]]|access-date=29 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThere is a general store in Byfield which caters for light meals as well as fuel and grocery items. Byfield has retreat style cabins and camping, offering accommodation in a rainforest setting with natural creeks and waterholes.\n\n== Education ==\nByfield State School is a government primary (Prep-6) school for boys and girls at 2233 Byfield Road ({{coord|-22.8412|150.6461|type:edu_region:AU-QLD|name=Byfield State School}}).<ref name=\"SchoolList2018\">{{cite web|url=https://data.qld.gov.au/dataset/state-and-non-state-school-details/resource/5b39065c-df32-415c-994c-5ff12f8de997|title=State and non-state school details|date=9 July 2018|publisher=[[Queensland Government]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121065959/https://data.qld.gov.au/dataset/state-and-non-state-school-details/resource/5b39065c-df32-415c-994c-5ff12f8de997|archivedate=21 November 2018|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.byfieldss.eq.edu.au|title=Byfield State School|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> In 2017, the school had an enrolment of 33 students with 3 teachers (2 full-time equivalent) and 5 non-teaching staff (2 full-time equivalent).<ref name=\"ACARA2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acara.edu.au/docs/default-source/default-document-library/school-profile-20172c7b12404c94637ead88ff00003e0139.xlsx?sfvrsn=0|title=ACARA School Profile 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122010027/http://www.acara.edu.au/docs/default-source/default-document-library/school-profile-20172c7b12404c94637ead88ff00003e0139.xlsx?sfvrsn=0|archivedate=22 November 2018|accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere is no secondary school in Byfield; the nearest is [[Yeppoon State High School]].<ref name=\"globe\">{{Queensland Globe|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Byfield, Queensland}}\n\n{{portal|Queensland}}{{Shire of Livingstone}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Queensland]]\n[[Category:Shire of Livingstone]]\n[[Category:Byfield, Queensland]]\n[[Category:Localities in Queensland]]\n\n\n{{Queensland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SDZeroBot", "label": "safe", "comment": "Stub sorting: replacing Queensland-geo-stub with CentralQueensland-geo-stub", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Byfield,_Queensland"}
{"title_page": "Ralph Sadler", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name               = Sir Ralph Sadlier\n|honorific-suffix   = [[Knight banneret]], [[Privy Council of England|PC]]\n|image              = An unidentified man (1) by Hans Holbein the Younger.jpg\n|imagesize          =\n|caption            =Possible portrait by [[Hans Holbein the Younger]]\n|order1             =\n|office1            = [[Secretary of State (England)|Secretary of State]]<ref>{{harvnb|Schofield|2011|p=374}} Held jointly with [[Thomas Wriothesley, 1st Earl of Southampton|Thomas Wriothesley]]</ref>\n|term_start1        = April 1540\n|term_end1          = 23 April 1543\n|monarch1           = [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]]\n|predecessor1       = [[Thomas Cromwell]]\n|successor1         = [[William Paget, 1st Baron Paget|William Paget]]\n|order2             =\n|office2            = [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]]\n|term_start2        = 16 May 1568\n|term_end2          = 15 June 1587\n|monarch2           = [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]]\n|predecessor2       = [[Ambrose Cave|Sir Ambrose Cave]]\n|successor2         = [[Francis Walsingham|Sir Francis Walsingham]]\n|birth_date         = 1507\n|birth_place        = [[Hackney (parish)|Hackney]], [[Middlesex]]\n|death_date         = 30 March {{Death year and age|1587|1507}}\n|death_place        = [[Standon, Hertfordshire]]\n|restingplace       = St. Mary's Church, [[Standon, Hertfordshire]]\n|restingplacecoordinates = {{Coord|51.881111|0.027222|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline}}\n|birthname          = Ralph Sadlier\n|nationality        =\n|party              =\n|spouse             = Ellen Barre\n|relations          =\n|children           = Thomas Sadler<br>Edward Sadlier<br>Henry Sadlier<br>Anne Sadlier<br>Mary Sadlier<br>Jane Sadlier<br>Dorothy Sadlier<br>Richard Sadlier\n|parents            = Henry Sadler\n|residence          =\n|alma_mater         =\n|occupation         =\n|profession         =\n|religion           = [[Church of England]]\n|signature          =\n|signature_alt      =\n}}\n'''Sir Ralph Sadler''' or '''Sadleir''' [[Privy Council of England|PC]], [[Knight banneret]]{{sfn|Coros|1982}} (1507 \u2013 30 March 1587;{{sfn|Coros|1982}} also spelled ''Sadleir'', ''Sadler'') was an [[England|English]] [[wikt:statesman|statesman]], who served [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] as [[Privy Council of England|Privy Councillor]], [[Secretary of State (England)|Secretary of State]] and [[ambassador]] to [[Scotland]]. Sadlier went on to serve [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]]. Having signed the device settling the crown on [[Lady Jane Grey|Jane Grey]] in 1553, he was obliged to retire to his estates during the reign of [[Mary I of England|Mary I]].{{sfn|Coros|1982}} Sadlier was restored to royal favour during the reign of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]], serving as a Privy Councillor and once again participating in Anglo-Scottish diplomacy. He was appointed [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]] in May 1568.{{sfn|Coros|1982}}\n[[File:Sutton House 1.jpg|thumbnail|237px|[[Sutton House, London|Sutton House]], Hackney, was built in 1535 by Sir Ralph Sadleir]]\n\n==Family and early life==\nRalph Sadler was born in [[Hackney (parish)|Hackney]], [[Middlesex]], the elder son of Henry Sadler,{{sfn|Henderson|1897|p=109}} a minor official in the service of the [[Thomas Grey, 2nd Marquess of Dorset|Marquess of Dorset]] and [[Edward Belknap|Sir Edward Belknap]].{{sfn|Drummond|1969|p=10|}} Henry Sadler was originally from [[Warwickshire]], but later settled in  Hackney.{{sfn|Coros|1982}} Ralph had a brother, John, who commanded a company at the [[Sieges of Boulogne (1544\u20131546)|Siege of Boulogne]] in 1544.{{sfn|Burke|1912|p=615}}\n\nAt around seven years of age, Sadler was placed in the household of [[Thomas Cromwell]], later [[Earl of Essex]], where he received an excellent education.{{sfn|Drummond|1969|p=10|}} He was taught to read and write,  becoming fluent in French, Latin and Greek and acquired a working knowledge of the law.{{sfn|Coros|1982}} He proved to be not only intelligent and resourceful, but also capable of great feats of horsemanship and was skilled at [[falconry]].{{sfn|Drummond|1969|p=11}} He was fortunate to find allocation of lodging at Court, without which an aspiring courtier had to seek permission from the King, and a potentially ruinous bill for accommodation near Hampton Court.  He pleaded with Cromwell that banishment from court would mean utter disgrace and penury.<ref>History of the King's Works; Weir (2001), p.31</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ascham]] compared Sadlier's appearance in terms of complexion, countenance and beard to [[Maurice, Elector of Saxony|Duke Maurice]], although the Duke was taller.{{sfn|Ascham|1904|p=[https://archive.org/stream/englishworkstoxo00aschuoft#page/162/mode/2up 163]}} Sadlier is also represented by his tomb effigy at Standon,{{sfn|Drummond|1969|pp=239\u2013240}}{{sfn|Stoney|1877|p=[https://archive.org/stream/cu31924027961683#page/n5/mode/2up i] plate of tomb}} and he may have been painted by [[Hans Holbein the Younger]].{{sfn|Gray|2000|pp=4\u20136}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Portrait of a Man (Sir Ralph Sadlier?)|work=The Metropolitan Museum of Art. Collections|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/Collections/search-the-collections/436668|publisher=Metmuseum.org|accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref>{{sfn|Parker|1945|loc=plate 33}}\n\n== Courtier and diplomat ==\nSadler began his career as secretary to Thomas Cromwell and went on to serve four [[Tudor period|Tudor]] monarchs. During his long career in royal service, he would hold many offices, including:{{sfn|Coros|1982}}\n* Clerk of the [[Hanaper]] 1535\u20131587\n* Gentleman of the Privy Chamber by May 1536\n* [[Ambassador]] to Scotland 1537, 1540, 1542\n* Jointly (with John Godsalve, Gregory Railton and Francis Kempe) prothonotary, Chancery 1537 \u2013 1587?\n* [[Secretary of State (England)|Principal Secretary]] April 1540 \u2013 April 1543\n* Privy Councillor 1540\u20131553, 1566\u20131587\n* [[Wardrobe (government)|Master of the Great Wardrobe]] 1543\u20131553\n* [[Justice of the Peace]] Hertfordshire 1544\u20131547, 1558/59 \u2013 1561, Gloucestershire 1547, Hertfordshire 1562\u20131587\n* Chamberlain or receiver, [[Court of General Surveyors]] by 1545\n* Commissioner for Musters, Hertfordshire 1546, loan 1546, 1562, goods of churches and fraternities 1550, relief, Hertfordshire and London 1550, ecclesiastical causes 1572\n* Steward of Hertford and Constable of Hertford Castle December 1549 \u2013 1554, 1559\u20131587\n* [[Lord Warden of the Marches|Warden of the East and Middle Marches]] 1559\u20131560\n* [[Custos rotulorum]] Hertfordshire. by 1562 \u2013 1587\n* [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]] 1568\u20131587\n* [[Lord Lieutenant]], Hertfordshire 1569\n\n===In the service of Cromwell and the King, 1536 to 1539===\nBy the time he was nineteen, Sadler was serving as Thomas Cromwell's secretary, learning about administration, finance and politics. In this role he handled Cromwell's household business and was also involved in drafting and writing his correspondence.  By 1529, he had become one of Cromwell's most trusted friends and was appointed as an executor of his will.{{sfn|Phillips|2004}} Between 1525 and 1529, his name appeared in Cromwell's correspondence in connection with suppression of monasteries.  It is probably around this time that his talents came to the attention of the king.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=993}} He was granted the manor and lands from the suppressed [[St Leonard's Priory, London|St Leonard's Priory]] in Bow.\n\nIt was probably soon after Cromwell's elevation to the peerage, on 9 July 1536, that Sadler was named a gentleman of the [[Privy Chamber]].{{sfn|Henderson|1897|p=109}}  In the same year, he became [[Member of Parliament|M.P.]] for [[Hindon (UK Parliament constituency)|Hindon, Wiltshire]]{{sfn|Coros|1982}} and his name also appears in the list of administrators named for [[Catherine of Aragon]]'s will.{{sfn|Strype I(II)|1822|p=[https://archive.org/stream/ecclesiasticalme0102stry#page/252/mode/2up 253]}}\n\nIn January 1537, Sadler was sent to [[Scotland]] to investigate complaints made by [[Margaret Tudor]], the King's sister, against her third husband, [[Henry Stewart, 1st Lord Methven]], and to improve Anglo-Scottish relations. He succeeded in both respects. On 1 April 1537, Ralph met [[James V of Scotland]], newly married to [[Madeleine of Valois]], at [[Rouen]].{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/stream/accountslordhig00treagoog#page/n78/mode/2up 21]}}\n\nThe King was pleased with Sadler's work, and sent him again to Scotland, this time to discourage the King of Scotland, James V, from accepting [[David Beaton|Cardinal Beaton's]] proposed Franco-Scottish alliance. Sadlier failed in that respect, but the King was nonetheless impressed with his work. In 1539 he was elected [[knight of the shire]] (MP) for [[Middlesex (UK Parliament constituency)|Middlesex]].\n\n=== Mr. Secretary: Henry VIII and Edward VI, 1540 to 1557 ===\nIn April 1540, Sadler was made [[Secretary of State (England)|principal secretary]] to the king, a position he held jointly with [[Thomas Wriothesley, 1st Earl of Southampton|Thomas Wriothesley]]. In the same year, he was knighted, made a [[privy councillor]], and began more than 30 years of service representing [[Hertfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Hertfordshire]] in Parliament. He represented [[Preston (UK Parliament constituency)|Preston]] in 1545.{{sfn|Coros|1982}}{{sfn|Phillips|2004}}\n\nSadler survived the fall from power and subsequent execution of his friend and mentor in 1540, however, during the power struggle following [[Gregory Cromwell#Arrest|Cromwell's demise]], he was arrested and sent to the [[Tower of London|Tower]].  On the evening of 17 January 1541, the [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Imperial]] ambassador, [[Eustace Chapuys]] and the French ambassador, [[Charles de Marillac]] reported to their masters that Sir Ralph Sadlier and [[Thomas Wyatt (poet)|Sir Thomas Wyatt]] had been arrested, as had another courtier [[Sir John Wallop]].  The following morning, they were taken from [[Hampton Court Palace|Hampton Court]], with their hands bound, accompanied by 24 archers, to the Tower.{{sfn|Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII|loc=16, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=76228 461]}}{{sfn|Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII|loc=16, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=76228 466]}} Marillac noted that it \"must be some great matter\" for Wyatt \"has for enemies all who leagued against Cromwell, whose minion he was.\"{{sfn|Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII|loc=16, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=76228 466]}}\n\nSadler was able to clear himself and was released in a few days, returning to the council chamber.{{sfn|Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII|loc=16|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=76228|ref= 470}} He played a leading role in the examination of Catherine Howard and her relatives in November 1541, regained the King's trust and was knighted for his part in holding matters of state while the court went on a summer progress of the North in a tripartite ministry with Lords Audley and Hertford.<ref>''Correspondance politique de MM De Castillon et de Marillac, ambassadeurs de France en Angleterre, 1537-42'' (ed. Jean Kaulek, Paris, 1885); Weir (2001), pp.448-50</ref>  Together with his allies in the council, notably [[Thomas Cranmer]], Sadlier gathered evidence in an unsuccessful attempt to discredit [[Thomas Howard, 3rd Duke of Norfolk|Norfolk]] and [[Stephen Gardiner|Gardiner]], the men who had orchestrated Thomas Cromwell's downfall. {{sfn|Phillips|2004}}\n\n=== From courtier to career diplomat: Mission to Scotland ===\n[[File:Linlithgow Palace Presence Chamber.jpg|thumb|right|[[Mary of Guise]] discussed politics with '''Ralph Sadler''' in her Presence Chamber at '''[[Linlithgow Palace]]''']]\nSadler was sent into Scotland to several times. In 1540 he tried to embarrass and undermine the authority of [[David Beaton|Cardinal Beaton]], an ally of France, with letters captured from his messenger [[Alexander Crichton of Brunstane]] whose ship had been forced by a storm to put into England. However, [[James V of Scotland]] refused to accept that the letters were compromising, and argued in favour of the Cardinal that he had a separate spiritual authority in Scotland apart from the King's own temporal powers. Later, when the Cardinal was present, James and Sadler compared the captured letters with Beaton's copies, and found a discrepancy. James V said he was thankful to Sadler and his uncle Henry VIII but still would not find fault in the Cardinal's actions.<ref>Arthur Clifford, ''Sadler State Papers'', vol.1 (Edinburgh, 1809), pp. 25-28, 42-44.</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Battle of Solway Moss]], Sadler was sent to Scotland again, in March 1543, to arrange a marriage between the infant [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], and [[Edward VI of England|Edward, Prince of Wales]]. He was a successful negotiator for the [[Treaty of Greenwich]], although the marriage was not concluded. On 22 March 1543 he rode from Edinburgh to [[Linlithgow Palace]] to see the queen for the first time. [[Mary of Guise]] showed him the queen out of her swaddling and Sadler wrote that the infant was \"as goodly a child I have seen, and like to live\". Mary reminded him that in turn [[Regent Arran]] wanted his son [[James Hamilton, 3rd Earl of Arran|James Hamilton]] to marry [[Elizabeth I of England|Princess Elizabeth]]. Mary tried to work on him to intercede for [[Regent Arran]] to release Cardinal Beaton from imprisonment, alleging the Cardinal's political expertise could be employed to mutual benefit.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/statepaperslette01sadluoft#page/86/mode/2up/ Arthur Clifford, ''Sadler State Papers'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1809), pp. 86-8].</ref> Henry VIII wanted English servants in Mary's household, and Sadler recommended \"Lady Edongcomb\" for this role, his friend the widow of [[Peter Edgecumbe (died 1539)|Peter Edgecumbe]] of [[Cotehele]].<ref>Arthur Clifford, ''Sadler State Papers'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1809), p. 230.</ref>\n[[File:Queen's Inner Hall, Stirling Castle (5897535215).png|thumb|left|'''Ralph Sadler''' talked to [[Mary of Guise]] in her Audience Chamber at [[Stirling Castle]]]]\nOn 10 August 1543 Sadler wrote to Henry VIII describing another visit to [[Mary of Guise]] and the infant Queen, this time at [[Stirling Castle]];<blockquote>\"(Mary of Guise) is very glad that she is at Stirling, and much she praised there about the house, and told me, \"That her daughter did grow apace; and soon,\" she said, \"she would be a woman, if she took of her mother;\" who indeed, is of the largest stature of women. And therefore she caused also the child to be brought to me, to the intent I might see her, assuring your majesty, that she is a right fair and goodly child, as any that I have seen for her age.\"{{sfn|Sadler I|1809|p=[https://archive.org/stream/statepaperslette01sadluoft#page/252/mode/2up 253]}}{{sfn|Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII|loc=18(2), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=76760 22]}}</blockquote>\n[[File:Tantallon Castle (3979724565).jpg|thumb|right|'''Ralph Sadler''' left Edinburgh for the safety of [[Tantallon Castle]]]]\nBy November Sadler, fearing for his safety as the mood in Edinburgh turned against England, moved to [[Tantallon Castle]], which belonged to the [[Archibald Douglas, 6th Earl of Angus|Earl of Angus]]. His commission to Scotland was revoked, and the [[Clan Douglas|Earl's kinsmen]] conveyed him to [[Berwick upon Tweed]] on 11 December 1543.{{sfn|Sadler I|1809|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/statepaperslette01sadluoft#page/346/mode/2up 346\u2013349]}}{{sfn|Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII|loc=18(2), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=76779 483]}} All of his work in solidifying Anglo-Scottish relations came to nothing, and war followed after the Scottish rejection of [[Treaty of Greenwich]] in December 1543.\n\nSadler was replaced by [[William Paget, 1st Baron Paget|William Paget]] as Secretary of State in April 1543, owing to his frequent absences on diplomatic missions, but was appointed [[Master of the Great Wardrobe]] and  accompanied [[Edward Seymour, 1st Duke of Somerset|the Earl of Hertford]], as treasurer for the war against Scotland, on a punitive expedition to [[Edinburgh]] in May 1544.  Sadlier accompanied Hertford once more into Scotland, in the same role, in September 1545.  He accompanied Lord Hertford again, this time at the [[Battle of Pinkie Cleugh]] in the post of High Treasurer of the Army.  On 10 September 1547, in recognition of his services during the fighting, Sadler was made a [[knight banneret]],.{{sfn|Coros|1982}}  Sadlier was present when [[Stephen Gardiner]], [[Bishop of Winchester]], was arrested, and he also accompanied the force that put down [[Robert Kett]]'s [[Kett's Rebellion|Norfolk Rebellion]].\n\nWhen Henry VIII was preparing his will on Boxing Day 1546, he had already appointed Sadler onto the Council of Regency that was to rule England during Edward VI's minority and left him \u00a3200 in his will.<ref>Weir (2001), p.499</ref>\n\nIn 1550 Sadler sold his mansion at Hackney. He was one of the signatories of Edward VI's will in 1553, proving one of the radicals in a Protestant government. He signed the device settling the crown on the [[Protestantism|Protestant]] Jane Grey, and was noted by [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley|Lord Burghley]] as one of those expected to act on her behalf.{{sfn|Coros|1982}}\n\n===Mary I and Elizabeth I, 1558 to 1587===\n[[File:Mary Queen of Scots by Nicholas Hilliard 1578.jpg|thumbnail|Miniature of Mary Stuart, Queen of Scots]]\nOn the accession of the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[Mary I of England|Mary I]] to the throne, after the resolution of the succession crisis, Sadler lost most of his offices, including [[Wardrobe (government)|master of the great wardrobe]], he was removed from the commissions of the peace and excluded from the Privy Council.{{sfn|Phillips|2004}} He was briefly under house arrest from 25 to 30 July 1553 before being granted a pardon on 6 October.{{sfn|Phillips|2004}} For the rest of Mary I's reign he did not sit in any parliament, remaining in semi-retirement at [[Standon, Hertfordshire]].{{sfn|Phillips|2004}}\n\nDuring the reign of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]], restored to royal favour, Sadler was sent to Scotland 8 August 1559 to arrange an alliance with the Scottish [[Protestantism|Protestants]], and forward the cause of the [[Lords of the Congregation]] and [[James Hamilton, 3rd Earl of Arran|Duke of Chatelherault]].{{sfn|Sadler I|1809|p=[https://archive.org/stream/statepaperslette01sadluoft#page/390/mode/2up 391]}}{{sfn|Calendar of State Papers, Scotland|loc=1, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=44050&strquery=Sadleyr#s11 520]}}  After the English became directly involved in the fighting at the [[Siege of Leith|Battle of Leith]], he was one of the architects of the [[Treaty of Edinburgh]].\n\nIn 1568 he was appointed [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]], and when Mary, Queen of Scots, fled to England, Sadler was unwillingly appointed to meet with the Scottish commissioners regarding that problem. He was sent to arrest the [[Thomas Howard, 4th Duke of Norfolk|Duke of Norfolk]] in Scotland in 1572 following the [[Rising of the North|Rising of the Northern Earls]]. He was reluctantly appointed [[jailer]] of Mary, Queen of Scots.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=993}}{{sfn|Henderson|1897|p=111}} From summer 1584 to spring 1585, Mary was housed at [[Wingfield Manor]]  and [[Tutbury Castle]], under Sadler's  charge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1558-1603/member/sadler-sir-ralph-1507-87|title=SADLER, Sir Ralph (1507-87), of Standon, Herts. - History of Parliament Online|website=www.historyofparliamentonline.org}}</ref> During that time, Elizabeth was nervous about Mary's plans against her. According to Andrea Clarke there was \"a tangible, palpable sense of heightened levels of fear among Elizabeth\u2019s government and ministers about her safety in the midst of the danger posed by Mary Queen of Scots, who for many Catholics was a figurehead\". Sadler was instructed to restrict Mary's freedom. [[Francis Walsingham]] chided Sadler for taking Mary \"hawkyng\" and for giving her \"more lybertye now then at any tyme when she was in the E of Shrewsbury chardge.\" Sadler was required to post guards round the castle and to search the grounds \"once or twice a moneth.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/these-letters-tell-inside-story-mary-queen-scots-imprisonment-180967762/|title=These Letters Tell the Inside Story of Mary, Queen of Scots\u2019 Imprisonment|first=Brigit|last=Katz|website=Smithsonian}}</ref> After the [[Babington Plot]], Sadler was on the council that sentenced Mary to death.{{sfn|Drummond|p=239}}\n\n==Marriage and issue==\nAround 1534,{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n284/mode/2up 261]|January to June 1835}} Ralph Sadler married Ellen, (daughter of John Mitchell, of [[Much Hadham]], [[Hertfordshire]]{{sfn|Phillips|2004}}), who at the time of their marriage was believed to be the widow of Matthew Barre (or Barrow) of [[Sevenoaks]] in [[Kent]].{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n284/mode/2up 260-264]|January to June 1835}} The couple had three sons and four daughters:{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n288/mode/2up 264]|January to June 1835}}\n[[File:Portrait of a Man (Sir Ralph Sadler?) MET DP278970.jpg|220px|thumb|right|Portrait of a Man (Sir Ralph Sadler?), 1535, Workshop of Hans Holbein the Younger ]]\n* Thomas Sadler of [[Standon, Hertfordshire]], (c. 1536 \u2013 1607),{{sfn|Phillips|2004}} named after [[Thomas Cromwell]], who succeeded him<ref>{{cite web|last=Salter|first=Colin|title=Sir Ralph Sadleir (1507-1587) and the Gossips|date=18 September 2010 |publisher=Talltalesfromthetrees.blogspot.com.au|url=http://talltalesfromthetrees.blogspot.com.au/2010/09/sir-ralph-sadleir-1507-1587-and-gossips.html|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref> married twice:{{sfn|Harvey et al|1884|p=136}}\n:* Ursula, daughter of John Sherington\n:* Gertrude, daughter of Robert Markham\n* Edward Sadler of [[Temple Dinsley]], (died 4 April 1584){{sfn|Stoney|1877|p=[https://archive.org/stream/cu31924027961683#page/n263/mode/2up 249]}} married Anne, daughter and heir of Sir Richard Lee of [[Sopwell, Hertfordshire]]{{sfn|Harvey et al|1884|p=136}}\n* Henry Sadler of [[Everleigh, Wiltshire]], (c. 1538 \u2013 1618),{{sfn|Phillips|2004}} married twice:{{sfn|Harvey et al|1884|p=136}}\n:* Mary, daughter of Gilbert Everley\n:* Ursula, daughter of John Gill\n* Anne Sadler (died 1576),{{sfn|Phillips|2004}} married George Horsey of [[Digswell]], Hertfordshire{{sfn|Harvey et al|1884|p=136}}\n* Mary Sadler married Thomas Bolle of [[Wallington, Hertfordshire]]{{sfn|Harvey et al|1884|p=136}}\n* Jane Sadler (died c. 1587),{{sfn|Phillips|2004}} married Edward Bash of Stanstedbury, Hertfordshire{{sfn|Harvey et al|1884|p=136}}\n* Dorothy Sadler (died c. 1578),{{sfn|Phillips|2004}} married Edward Elrington of Byrchall, Essex{{sfn|Harvey et al|1884|p=136}}\n\nSadler may have had an illegitimate son, Richard.{{sfn|Phillips|2004}}{{sfn|Stoney|1877|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/cu31924027961683#page/n261/mode/2up 247] footnote}}\n\n===The return of Matthew Barre===\n[[File:St Mary, Standon, Herts - geograph.org.uk - 361615.jpg|thumbnail|right|St. Mary's Church, [[Standon, Hertfordshire]], where Sadler is buried]] More than eleven years after Ralph and Ellen had married, Matthew Barre returned alive and well from Ireland and was overheard in a London tavern claiming to be the lawful husband of Sadler's wife.{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n284/mode/2up 261]|January to June 1835}}{{sfn|Drummond|1969|p=12}} Ralph and his wife had seven surviving children, and he was now a very wealthy and influential person at court whose reputation was at stake. Sadler, a man devoted to his wife and children, was informed of the matter in October 1545 while on a diplomatic mission in Scotland.{{sfn|Drummond|1969|p=12, 14}} \"Master Sadler took his matter very heavily,\" the [[Lord Chancellor]], [[Thomas Wriothesley, 1st Earl of Southampton|Wriothesley]] reported to Secretary [[William Paget, 1st Baron Paget|Paget]].{{sfn|Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII|loc=20(2), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=80427 697]}}\n\nEllen Mitchell and Matthew Barre had been legally married in 1526, in [[Great Dunmow|Dunmow]] in Essex.{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n284/mode/2up 261]|January to June 1835}} They had two daughters before Barre abandoned them and went to Ireland.{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n284/mode/2up 261]|January to June 1835}} Ellen stayed in Dunmow for about a year trying to find out where he had gone.{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n284/mode/2up 261]|January to June 1835}} She then became a servant of the prioress at the nunnery of Clerkenwell.{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n284/mode/2up 261]|January to June 1835}} Determined to find Matthew, she visited his birthplace and with his brothers made further enquiries, but without success. Despairing of an answer she returned to Clerkenwell.{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n284/mode/2up 261]|January to June 1835}} Not long afterwards a man belonging to the city of Salisbury positively assured her that her husband was dead.{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n284/mode/2up 261]|January to June 1835}} Recommended by the Prioress of Clerkenwell, Ellen entered the service of Thomas Cromwell's mother-in-law, Mercy Pryor, and was dwelling in his house when Ralph Sadler became enamoured of her.{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n284/mode/2up 261]|January to June 1835}} Ralph Sadler and Ellen married believing that Matthew Barre was dead.{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n284/mode/2up 261]|January to June 1835}}\n\nA version of Ellen's story was given by an Elizabethan writer, [[Nicholas Sanders|Nicolas Sander]], and cast doubt on her character.{{sfn|Sander|1877|p=[https://archive.org/stream/riseofschism00sanduoft#page/176/mode/2up 176\u2013177] and footnotes}} Sander claimed that Ellen was related to Thomas Cromwell, and that she had worked for him as a laundress.{{sfn|Sander|1877|p=[https://archive.org/stream/riseofschism00sanduoft#page/176/mode/2up 176\u2013177] and footnotes}}{{sfn|Harvey|p=65 Ellen may have been employed a laundress in Thomas Cromwell's household, where she met Ralph Sadler, however, the rest of Sander's story is without foundation}} The 17th-century historian [[Gilbert Burnet]] considered that Sander's story was a fiction.{{sfn|Burnet|1865|p=[https://archive.org/stream/historyofreforma05burniala#page/592/mode/2up 593]|}} Sander was a [[Jesuit]], a Catholic [[recusant]] writing with an agenda. He took delight in attempting to discredit leading public figures in England.{{sfn|Stoney|1877|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/cu31924027961683#page/n27/mode/2up 13\u201314]}} There was no scandal surrounding the marriage between Ellen and Ralph when it took place.\n\nAn investigation found that Ellen's first marriage was valid, and Sadler was therefore obliged to have his children legitimised by a private Act of Parliament.{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n284/mode/2up 261\u2013262]|January to June 1835}} In 1546, this Act of Parliament ''37 Hen. VIII, c.30''{{sfn|Coros|1982}}{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n286/mode/2up 262-264]<br />Transcript of ''An Act for the Legitimation of the children of Sir Ralph Sadler, Knight'', passed in anno 37 Henry VIII. No. 28 [Transcript in Harl. MS 7089, f. 453] is presented here|January to June 1835}} was passed on his behalf.{{sfn|Coros|1982}}{{sfn|The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle|loc=III:[https://archive.org/stream/gentlemansmagaz70unkngoog#page/n286/mode/2up 262-264]<br />Transcript of ''An Act for the Legitimation of the children of Sir Ralph Sadler, Knight'', passed in anno 37 Henry VIII. No. 28 [Transcript in Harl. MS 7089, f. 453] is presented here|January to June 1835}} The Act set aside Ellen's marriage to Matthew Barre and made her marriage to Ralph Sadler a true and proper union. Sadler managed to prevent the publication of the Act and its details never appeared among the statutes of the period.{{sfn|Drummond|1969|p=14}} The only known contemporary reference to the Act appears in a transcript entitled ''The Unprecedented Case of Sir Ralph Sadleir'' in the Library of the [[Inner Temple]].<ref>''A Catalogue of the Printed Books and Manuscripts in the Library of the Inner Temple, arranged in classes'' (C. & W. Galabin, Ingram Court, London 1833), p. 116-18, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=chi.42148901;view=1up;seq=226 at p. 118] (Hathi Trust), citing benchmark: Press 5, Shelf 3, No. 535, Vol. 6, p. 335.</ref> Matthew Barre disappeared from the scene.{{sfn|Drummond|1969|p=14}}\n\nThis episode damaged Sadler's reputation, but not irretrievably. His marriage to Ellen was saved and the couple lived on, without further incident, for many years.{{sfn|Drummond|1969|p=15}}\n\n== Death ==\nSadler's wife was still living in 1569;{{sfn|Drummond|1969|p=214}}{{sfn|Stoney|1877|p=[https://archive.org/stream/cu31924027961683#page/n29/mode/2up 14]}} however, there is no further record of her and there is no surviving tomb for her.{{sfn|Drummond|1969|p=239}} Sir Ralph died 30 March 1587,{{sfn|Coros|1982}} reputedly, \"the richest commoner in England.\"{{sfn|Sadler I|1809|p=[https://archive.org/stream/statepaperslette01sadluoft#page/n43/mode/2up xxxii]}} His tomb lies beneath a magnificent wall monument in St. Mary's Church, [[Standon, Hertfordshire]].{{sfn|Phillips|2004}}{{sfn|Stoney|1877|p=[https://archive.org/stream/cu31924027961683#page/n255/mode/2up 241]}} He left the majority of his vast landholdings, including Standon and Buntingford, Hertfordshire, to his eldest son and heir, Thomas Sadlier.{{sfn|Phillips|2004}} Henry Sadler received the manors of Hungerford, Berkshire, and Everley, Wiltshire, Jane Bash received a diamond ring and an annuity was provided for Richard Sadler.{{sfn|Phillips|2004}}<ref>Richard Sadlier may have been an illegitimate son, or his grandson, the second son of Edward Sadler. see {{harvnb|Burke|1912|p=[https://archive.org/stream/genealogicalhera00burkuoft#page/612/mode/2up 616]}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\nSadler is one of the few Renaissance statesmen for whom extant Parliamentary orations survive, including a speech on succession in 1563 and one on subsidy in 1566. Copies of the orations appear the 1809 two-volume publication of his letters, which includes a biography by [[Walter Scott]].{{sfn|Sadler I|1809}}{{sfn|Sadler II|1809}}\n\n==Fictional portrayals==\n\nSadler is one of the major characters in [[Hilary Mantel]]'s 2009 novel ''[[Wolf Hall]]'', which gives a fictional portrayal of Sadler's youth and early manhood in the household of [[Thomas Cromwell]]. During the [[BBC 2]] series, he is portrayed by [[Thomas Brodie-Sangster]]. Sadler also appears prominently in ''[[Bring Up the Bodies]]'' and ''[[The Mirror and the Light|The Mirror & the Light]]'', Mantel's sequels to ''[[Wolf Hall]]''. He is also a minor character in [[Philippa Gregory]]'s book ''[[The Other Queen]]'', with an account given of the time he spent as the [[Mary, Queen of Scots|Queen of Scots]]' gaoler.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Secretary of State (England)]]\n* [[Privy Councillor]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ascham\n  |first=Roger\n  |author-link=Roger Ascham\n  |editor=Wright, William Aldis\n  |chapter=A Report and Discourse of the Affaires and State of Germany ...\n  |title=English Works: Toxophilus; Report and Discourse of the Affaires and State of Germany; The Scholemaster\n  |series=Cambridge English Classics\n  |location=Cambridge\n  |publisher=Cambridge University Press\n  |year=1904\n  |pages=121\u2013169\n  |url=https://archive.org/stream/englishworkstoxo00aschuoft#page/120/mode/2up\n  |ref={{sfnref|Ascham|1904}}\n}}\n* {{cite book |last=Burke\n  |first=Bernard\n  |author-link=Bernard Burke\n  |title=Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Landed Gentry of Ireland\n  |year=1912\n  |publisher=Harrison & Sons\n  |loc